B0$ Felt like from our team only he (Rashid) turned up. The way he batted, the way he bowled, it was tremendous. Don't have to try much (after this result). As a group we weren't there. B0$: The Indian Premier League rolls onto Mumbai's Wankhede stadium tonight with the Gujarat Titans facing the Mumbai Indians in what should be a high-scoring affair. The hosts have become successful chasers of high scores in recent times and they ambushed the Royals Challengers in their last game here at home. A flat pitch, nice even bounce and short boundaries have become a bowler's nightmare at the Wankhede, but the hosts are up against a big challenge in the form of the table toppers. A win will confirm a top-2 finish for the Titans and they'll be cheered every ball by a host of franchises, especially those whose fortunes is directly linked to MI's result tonight.

B0$     
  
Thank God, I am retired." Harbhajan Singh, one of India's finest white ball spinners of all-time, heaved a sigh of relief while speaking informally to journalists after the last game at the Wankhede the other night (on May 9). Mumbai Indians had just sauntered to a target of 200 in a wink - in just about 16 overs that is. That was a high-speed chase against bowlers of the calibre of Josh Hazlewood, Mohammed Siraj, Wanindu Hasaranga and Harshal Patel.   
   
It's no rocket science that the playing conditions and surface conditions have made life difficult for the bowlers. Totals of 200 have become a norm this IPL season across the board and the Wankhede has been no exception. The last three games at the ground saw chases of over 200-run targets - MI knocked off 213 versus Rajasthan Royals on April 30 and ended up at 201 for six while pursuing a target of 215 on April 22.   
   
The surface at the stadium has become a belter - the bowlers' nightmare -- and Harbhajan had once labelled such pitches as highways. It has been run-fests all along and it is unlikely the proceedings will be any different here on Friday night when Mumbai Indians and Gujarat Titans, two power house sides with some in-form batsmen, will clash.   
   
   
"To have fresh batters is really important. We try to bowl outside their hitting arcs, make the batters hit in our areas," said Jason Behrendorff, the Mumbai pacer on ways to stem the flow of runs. Teammate Kumar Kathikeya added: "T20 is a batters game. Nowadays batters hit 360 degrees, so as a bowler, it is important to focus on the basics. We just try to control the run rate."   
   
Vikram Solanki, the director of cricket of the Titans side, agreed. "Take wickets," he said, as the answer to batsmen on a rampage. "It's tough for the bowlers. The batsmen are pushing the boundaries. They should also because it is the premier competition. Equally, the bowlers respond somehow. They are coming up with plans with their own ways of controlling. But it has been tough this year. The impact player rule means the batting line-ups have lengthened.   
   
"The bowlers do find ways to control. That might very well be different from one bowler to the next. But our sort of mindset is to try and be as attacking as possible. The best way to control the run rate is to take wickets," Solanki explained the point. "We've got a very experienced group and it is very well led by Mohammed Shami. He sets the example for the rest to follow."   
   
With some power hitters in both sides, like Ishan Kishan, Suryakumar Yadav, Cameron Green, Tim David, Tilak Varma, Shubman Gill, Wriddhiman Saha, Hardik Pandya, Vijay Shankar and Rahul Tewatia, another big score of over 200 and an equally gallant chase are expected.   
   
But the focus could be mainly on a certain Rohit Sharma. Mumbai Indians will need their skipper, who has been out of sorts this IPL (just 191 runs in 11 games), to fire so that their chances of progressing to the next stage increase. With Suryakumar, who had made a mockery of a 200-run chase in the last game, around, the five-time champions are able to wriggle out of tough chases but the team cannot rely upon always. The captain has to come to the party before it is too late as the game is more important for the home team (12 from 11 games) than the visitors (16 from 11 games).
